<seg id=1> Chuan Leekpai: Thailand to Hold General Election in Advance </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Bangkok exclusive) Thailand Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the night before last that he will hold a general election in advance, before the term expiration of the united government of seven parties in October 2000. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He added that the status of the coalition government was currently stable, and it was competent to carry out the plan of economic reform. </seg>
<seg id=4> He said that economic reform was vital to the resuscitation of the economy and to reach a level of sustainable development. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Chuan Leekpai said when giving speech at the Thailand Overseas Communication Club Supper, "the confidence of foreign investors was definitely closely linked to the stability of government and enforcement of policy, and we will fix it." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "we don't plan to wait up until the expiration of the term. </seg>
<seg id=7> We'll make use of the time left to try our best to carry out reorganization of the nation's economy, and to create a steady foundation for stable development (in the future)." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leekpai expressed that it had not been decided to dismiss the Congress and hold the general election in advance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand has not rid itself of crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Furthermore, Chuan Leekpai warned in his speech that Thailand had not gotten rid of crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He pointed out that the current status was still "fragile", international factors might still direct Thailand to depart from the objective of turning around the economy in late 1999. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> But, he promised to carry out reform measures on a large scale and stop the corruption ethos that had weakened the nation's economy. </seg>
</p>
